{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \D7, fourth-best from your longest suit — a normal, safe start against the spade game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Partner's 4\D was a splinter — a game raise of spades with diamond shortness — and you are in 4\S needing ten tricks. The suit to study is clubs: dummy's \CA-Q-J-T-9 opposite your singleton 3. That is the classic RUFFING FINESSE shape. Cash the ace first — your singleton goes on it — and then run dummy's honors through East: if East covers with the king, ruff it; if East plays low, throw a loser from your hand. The club suit will hand you trick after trick without ever losing one to the king.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \D7 to your jack. Play a spade to dummy's ace — and East's KING drops, a singleton! Now the clubs: cash the \CA (your 3 falls), then lead the \C9 — East plays low, so pitch a heart loser; the nine WINS. Next the \CT — now East covers with the king, and you ruff it away. Dummy's \CQ-J stand over everything, ready to swallow more losers. Cash your diamonds and concede only the \HA, a club ruff, and the trump queen: ten tricks.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Dummy's five-card club sequence never lost a trick to the king: the ace first, then the honors ran through East — low meant a free pitch, the cover met a ruff. That is the ruffing finesse doing its work in a suit contract, and the stiff trump king under the ace was the day's bonus. Nicely played.}
